76561198027212551,Recommended,404530,35009388,Posted: 16 September,all,thebobster,"Accidentally cancelled out of my own review, so I'll just put the short version up for now :xSo far it's really neat, and while no one part (combat, driving, property management, UI design) is spectacular, it's neat to see all of these ideas coming together and interacting. As a criminal, you get to see the damages and other effects of your criminal empire on the world itself, and as a property investor/developer you get to explore your city and see/interact/build with the interiors and people in each buildings. After doing some missions eliminating bandits and doing some experimentation in my own base, I was able to purchase and customize my own office building, and it's fun to work on that while being able to see people and cars moving around in the streets below (and sometimes going to the nearby skyscrapers for rooftop sniper battles when the bandits cause a ruckus).The price is cheap for how ambitious the project is, and the devs have been active so far in fixing up game issues, and they even created templetes for various types of gamemods for the steam workshop. If the idea of being able to explore and mess with a world with a lot of moving parts, or anything else I've mentioned above, sounds interesting to you, I would definitely check it out. If you're like me and want to learn more about what you can do in the game, the devs set up about 12 or so articles on indiedb (I think you can access them from the updates list, but I don't want to accidentally delete my review again while checking) explaining all of the various mechanics.Also I couldn't find a place to put this in my review, so I'll just mention here that the music is pretty amazing. It shows up sparsely, but when it does (usually when building or in combat) it's a real treat."
